{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9f7883f2-5cb4-422b-b57f-a585f20e8d15","content":"In ASP.NET Core, **Scoped** means \"per HTTP request\" — each request gets a fresh `DbContext`. But MAUI has **no HTTP requests**, so there's no natural scope boundary. Without one, `AddScoped` behaves essentially like `AddSingleton` — you get **one `DbContext` for the entire app lifetime**.\n\nThat's why your tracked entities persist across navigations: the same context (and its change tracker) is reused everywhere.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — each injection gets a new instance.\n2. **Use `IDbContextFactory<T>`** and create/dispose contexts manually:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>(opts =>\n       opts.UseSqlite(\"...\"));\n   ```\n   Then in your page/viewmodel:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _factory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n3. If you truly need scoped behavior, you'd have to **manually create `IServiceScope`s**, but the factory approach is simpler and recommended for MAUI.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0099df73-2f74-4eff-b81a-966282dae89a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when using dependency injection (DI) in .NET MAUI with Entity Framework Core's DbContext. This is a conceptual question, not a code task, so I can answer directly.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, \"Scoped\" lifetime means per-HTTP-request. But MAUI doesn't have HTTP requests — there's no built-in scope boundary. So `AddScoped` in MAUI effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, meaning the same DbContext instance lives for the entire app lifetime. That's why data \"persists\" across page navigations.","outputTokens":421,"requestId":"100B:1F50C6:15EB0FB:1896CF7:69FD3688"},"id":"162ceba7-9cfc-4793-b17a-22ff089fe1ba","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:04:19.670Z","parentId":"52aee1aa-ee95-4368-8846-13b9d4f7c292"}
